    "summary": "The Papal States (formally established 754–756 AD when the Frankish king Pepin III donated conquered territories to the papacy after defeating the Lombards) were the territorial possessions of the Catholic Church in central Italy that gave the papacy independent political sovereignty for over a thousand years — until Italian unification absorbed them in 1870. The Donation of Pepin (754/756 AD) — territories around Rome including the Exarchate of Ravenna, previously held by Byzantium — was justified by the forged 'Donation of Constantine,' a document (exposed as fraudulent by Lorenzo Valla in 1440) that purported to show Emperor Constantine giving the pope temporal authority over the western empire.\n\nThe Papal States' existence fundamentally shaped medieval European politics and the papacy's character. As a temporal ruler, the pope needed armies, diplomats, and revenues — concerns that inevitably entangled the papacy in the brutal politics of Italian city-states and pan-European power struggles. The wealth and territory gave the papacy independence from any single secular ruler, enabling it to be a genuinely transnational authority; but it also corrupted many medieval popes who treated the church as an instrument of their political and familial ambitions. The tension between spiritual mission and temporal power — what critics called the 'Babylonian Captivity of the Church' — produced reformers from Arnold of Brescia to Erasmus to Luther who argued that the church's temporal power had corrupted its spiritual mission. The loss of the Papal States in 1870 ironically freed the papacy to be more effectively spiritual; the 1929 Lateran Treaty created the current Vatican City state.",
